Twenty-four years ago, our country endured the most vicious terrorist attack in American history, which took the lives of 3,000 of our fellow Americans. On September 11th, we remember the mothers, fathers, sons, and daughters we tragically lost and reflect on the greatest qualities of the American people—courage, heroism and compassion—that shined through the darkness of that day. In particular, we honor the courageous first responders who risked their own lives to save others, as well as our brave military service members who brought the fight to the enemy and laid down their lives to protect our country. May God continue to bless the United States of America.
September 11, 2001. Never Forget.

Political violence is abhorrent and has absolutely no place in our country. We may have differences, but we are all Americans. 

Charlie Kirk tragically died fighting for what he believed in: freedom—freedom of speech, freedom of thought, and freedom to organize. He not only championed those ideals, particularly for the next generation, he embodied them. The best way to honor Charlie’s memory is to keep challenging ideas, defending free speech, and pursuing open and civil debate that strengthens our society and our country. 

May Charlie rest in peace, and may God bless his young family.
Sending prayers to Charlie Kirk, his family, and everyone at the event in Utah.

I worked relentlessly to make sure the OBBB is full of wins for Alaska—strengthening rural health care, investing in Arctic defense, flexibility on Medicaid/SNAP work requirements, protecting our vulnerable communities, and unleashing Alaskan energy. Alaska has unique challenges, but we are also uniquely positioned to help America.

80 years ago, America’s Greatest Generation risked their lives, defended freedom, and secured victory in World War II. Alaska played a pivotal role. We fought Japanese forces after they invaded the Aleutian Islands. Our state also became a vital launch point for our forces in the Pacific.

Today, as new threats from Russia & China are on the rise, one of the best ways we honor the legacy of those who fought to keep us free is by maintaining a strong and unmatched military. The One Big Beautiful Bill does exactly that: $29 billion to bolster U.S. Navy shipbuilding, a $25 billion down payment on the Golden Dome missile defense system, $25 billion for our Coast Guard, and billions to support our warfighters and their families.
 
We will never forget the sacrifice of those who came before us—and we will ensure Alaska continues to stand as the cornerstone of our nation’s defense.

Today we honor Alaska’s hardworking men and women—our builders, laborers, public safety officers, fishermen, pipe fitters, miners, nurses, teachers, military service members, pilots, electricians, building trades, and truck drivers—just some of the many professions that make our state the greatest state, in the greatest country on earth. My number one focus as a U.S. Senator has been working with Alaskans to create a strong economy and good paying jobs. That is the main reason why I started the Senate Labor and Hardworking Americans Caucus last year to focus on the issues that matter most to working families. Because of The One Big Beautiful Bill, and so many other successes we’ve had, billions in private sector, federal, and military investments are on the horizon and the need for a strong, well-trained Alaskan workforce has never been greater. We are a state blessed with vast resources, but our working families are our most valuable resource by far. To all of our incredible workers, thank you for everything you do for our state and country, and Happy Labor Day!

For the 5th time this week, our military intercepted a Russian surveillance aircraft in Alaska’s ADIZ. Alaska is on the frontlines: We must strengthen our military with Alaska as the cornerstone. From the Golden Dome missile defense system and reopening Naval Base Adak to jumpstarting shipbuilding and historic investments in our Coast Guard, the OBBB delivers.

The strategic importance of Alaska has been demonstrated time and time again this summer. Just in the last few days, there have been two Russian incursions into our airspace, which our Alaska-based military, once again, professionally intercepted and sent packing back to Russia. Additionally, our military and Coast Guard have been closely monitoring Chinese vessels in the Arctic Ocean near our EEZ that are supposedly conducting research—potentially as a cover for more nefarious objectives. But most importantly, all branches of our military and some allied partners, have been conducting two important military exercises in our state throughout August—Arctic Edge and Northern Edge—to train homeland security, combat readiness, and power projection capabilities in the Arctic and Indo-Pacific in the event of a major contingency with one of our adversaries.

The training in Alaska of our military, particularly the Joint Pacific-Alaska Range Complex (JPARC), is unrivaled anywhere in the world. As part of this exercise and challenging training, top uniformed and civilian leaders have come to Alaska, including INDOPACOM Commander Admiral Sam “Pappy” Paparo, NORTHCOM Commander Greg “Clete” Guillot, Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Admiral Chris Grady, and importantly the Assistant Secretary of Defense for Energy, Installations and Environment, the Honorable Dale Marks, whose portfolio is critical to Alaska. I‘ve traveled around the state with these fine military officers and leaders—including visits to JBER, Fort Greely, and meetings with the 11th Airborne Division—to watch the outstanding training throughout Alaska this month. I want to thank all of them for being up here and, in particular, thank Admiral Grady, who will be retiring in September after 42 years of Naval service to our great nation.

We discussed all kinds of important issues for Alaska and our nation, including plans to reopen the naval base at Adak on the Aleutian Island Chain, Alaska energy for our forces, and the importance of increased Naval and Marine Corps presence and operations in Alaska. In that regard, I had the opportunity to fly out to the USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72) carrier strike group off the coast of Alaska, which is participating in Northern Edge. It is remarkable and humbling to watch a carrier strike group in operation knowing that the average age of the over 5,000 sailors and Marines on the USS Abraham Lincoln—one of the great instruments of American power—is about 23 years old. These brave service members are conducting important operations that establish credible deterrence in the North Pacific and help mold the sailors and aviators of the strike group into the most lethal force on planet earth. Of course, on that visit, I had the honor of visiting with some young Alaskans who are deployed aboard the Lincoln, all of whom make us all very proud.

Big news for Alaska and the Arctic: A nearly $400 million contract has been awarded to expand the Port of Nome! This contract is an important milestone in building out America’s first deep-water Arctic port to strengthen America’s presence in the Arctic, bolster our national security, and provide economic opportunities for Northwest Alaska.

Since I’ve been in office, I’ve used my seats on the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee and the Senate Armed Services Committee to secure federal support for this project, including increasing the federal cost-share for the project. The Port of Nome is more than infrastructure—it’s a strategic gateway to the Arctic, and one of the latest great investments in Alaska military might that will ensure the U.S. is a leader in Arctic security, trade, and influence.

Pursuing peace is difficult, complicated, and risky. The Trump administration is spending much political capital and taking risks for peace. Since Russia’s brutal invasion of Ukraine, I have been a strong supporter of Ukraine, including by providing weapons to Ukraine and our NATO allies and hitting Russia with severe sanctions. I want to commend President Trump and his entire team for the relentless time and energy they have put into trying to stop the slaughter in Ukraine launched by the dictator, Putin—like they are doing in so many other places in the world: Azerbaijan and Armenia, Cambodia and Thailand, Israel and Iran, Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of the Congo, India and Pakistan, Egypt and Ethiopia, Serbia and Kosovo, and, of course, the Abraham Accords.

I also want to thank President Trump and his team for taking the time to meet with me, my wife, Julie, our entire delegation, and the governor. Friday was a high-pressure day of intense world diplomacy. Despite this, the President and his team—including Secretary of State Rubio, Secretary of Defense Hegseth, Secretary of Commerce Lutnick, Secretary of the Treasury Bessent, Special Envoy Steve Witkoff, White House Chief of Staff Susie Wiles, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff General Caine, and the Supreme Allied Commander General Grynkewich—all took the time to meet with me when they touched down in our great state. That was much appreciated.

Finally, to my fellow Alaskans—so many of whom worked so hard on security for the Alaska Summit and on welcoming people and media from all over the world to our state—we have much to be proud of from the Alaska Summit. Thank you and congratulations on showing the world what a great state we live in and just how strategically vital we are for America’s national and energy security. In particular, I want to thank our remarkable Alaska-based military and law enforcement. You were given an incredibly important mission on a short time frame. And whether it was undertaking security operations for the world leaders at the Alaska Summit, staging our world-class military assets—like dozens of 5th generation fighters—for all the world to see, or conducting well-timed flyovers to demonstrate to our adversaries the might of the U.S. military, you all conducted this important mission flawlessly. I took a video of this flyover which included our Alaska-based F-35s and a B-2, and was honored to later meet with the B-2 pilots who conducted it.

Thank you all for your hard work and professionalism.

This year, Juneau has experienced a record level of flooding from the annual glacial lake outburst flood (GLOF) down the Mendenhall River—over 16.5 feet—topping last year’s record of 15.99 feet. In light of these serious challenges and the threat to the lives and property of Alaskans, I have been very focused on getting federal dollars and a workable enduring plan from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to fix this annual challenge in one of our biggest cities. Like I did in the aftermath of last year’s Juneau flood, I wanted to assess the damage as soon as possible this summer and begin the important work on a durable engineering solution to this problem, which is why I spent all day in Juneau today.
 
This morning, I took a helicopter tour of Mendenhall Glacier and the flood zone. I then participated in a very detailed briefing and roundtable discussion with the Unified Command team, including the City and Borough of Juneau, the Central Council of the Tlingit-Haida, the Army Corps of Engineers (USACE), the Coast Guard, the Forest Service, the National Weather Service, and the State of Alaska. I want to commend everyone in the community for their incredible coordination, which no doubt saved lives.
 
Regarding next steps, the Corps is a critical partner in both the short-term and in the long-term, enduring solution. That is why, at my request, the recently confirmed Assistant Secretary of the Army for Civil Works, Adam Telle, sent his top leadership for the Pacific Ocean Division—Brigadier General Goetz—to be on the ground immediately to see the situation for himself. Earlier this year, Assistant Secretary Telle committed to me to expedite a solution for Juneau—not simply accepting another 10 years of studies. The HESCO barriers that were donated by the Corps have overall proven to be a “wild success,” according to the city and the Corps, saving an estimated 1,000 homes from being flooded—but they didn’t work perfectly. 
 
I truly want to commend USACE Brigadier General Goetz and Command Sergeant Major Zachary Plummer for their outstanding work, and all the time they have spent in the last week on the ground in Juneau, providing reassurance to the citizens of our capital city. I also want to thank Assistant Secretary Telle for already keeping his commitment to me that he would focus his senior team’s efforts on helping Juneau. 
 
I look forward to continue working with all of the stakeholders in Juneau and the Corps to expedite a long-term solution for this community, leveraging the important provisions in President Trump’s Day One executive order, Unleashing Alaska’s Extraordinary Resource Potential, which gives the Corps extraordinary powers to work on important Alaska projects, like this one.

House minority leader Hakeem Jeffries told Americans point blank: “Not a single undocumented immigrant in this country gets a dime in federal taxpayer dollars for any part of comprehensive Medicaid coverage.”

So why did Senate Democrats just challenge and then vote to remove an amendment in the Senate bill ensuring illegal immigrants WON’T get Medicaid? First we’re told the problem doesn’t exist, and now Democrats are fighting to save it.

Sounds like some far-left dishonest liberals are in a tizzy over my telling of the facts of what is going on in D.C. right now. Here again are the facts:

During a debate of a budget reconciliation bill, which we are involved with right now, the parliamentarian of the Senate rules on whether provisions violate the so-called Byrd rule. But the Byrd rule is not self-executing. The parliamentarian does not scrub the bill to look for violations. Bill provisions must be challenged by Democrat leadership for her to rule on whether a provision violates the Byrd rule.

Democrats in the Senate, led by Chuck Schumer, are challenging every single provision in this bill that would benefit Alaska. The most notorious, as I mentioned last night, is my provision that I’ve been working on for years to increase the federal match for Medicaid for Alaska, which was in the bill and supported by all Republicans and the White House, and would’ve provided Alaska hundreds of millions of dollars more a year in federal Medicaid money. Far-left-wing affiliated Democrat groups are running blatantly false attack ads against me in Alaska saying this bill would cut Medicaid and Medicare benefits in Alaska. This is false.

But here is an undeniable fact: The only people cutting Medicaid for Alaskans right now—hundreds of millions of dollars each year from the federal government—are Chuck Schumer and Senate Democrats. Period.

They also challenged a provision of mine that made it into the budget reconciliation bill to increase funding for rural hospitals in Alaska and Hawaii. Schumer and the Democrats challenged that and successfully stripped it out yesterday, trying to hurt rural hospitals in Alaska. But we will continue to fight the anti-Alaska Democrats in the Senate.

Here are just a few of the other things Schumer and the Senate Democrats have challenged with the parliamentarian that were in the budget reconciliation bill that would dramatically help Alaska. Remember, this is a fact: Schumer and the Senate Democrats are trying to rip all these things out of the budget reconciliation bill to harm Alaskans.
